texts.html: After much fanfare including a mundane video teaser, HTC just released the first part of their latest advertising campaign. Starring Robert “Iron Man” Downey Jr. the video spot is, well, memorable. It’s a touch crazy, a bit confusing, and doesn’t showcase anything HTC makes. But you won’t forget it. And that’s what makes for an effective ad.

text: After much fanfare including a mundane video teaser, HTC just released the first part of their latest advertising campaign. Starring Robert “Iron Man” Downey Jr. the video spot is, well, memorable. It’s a touch crazy, a bit confusing, and doesn’t showcase anything HTC makes. But you won’t forget it. And that’s what makes for an effective ad.

texts.html: As Natasha explained when HTC released the teaser, HTC is asking, almost rhetorically, what their initials stand for. Like “Humongous Tinfoil Catamaran” and ”Hipster Troll Carwash,” says the ad. You get it. Hyper Tongue Circus. Hello, Titicaca Coast. Hippopotamuses Tightroping Carelessly.

texts.html: There’s good reason for this. Despite being a major player in Android since the very beginning, HTC isn’t a household name. These clever, and mostly silly acronyms, will act as a sort of mnemonic for the brand.

texts.html: Because, really, anything is better than High Tech Computer Corporation, which is what the initials really stand for. Not very catchy.

texts.html: This video could've started with them entering the initial boardroom meeting. "Ok people focus up!" I like the idea of figuring out what HTC means because I never knew. (Don't think I cared but now I do). What's good is that it's a simple and fun idea. I think that instead of blowing the wad here they should break it up into several spots and turn to Twitter to have users submit their best ideas for what HTC means. Produce spots around the most entertaining ideas. Have people vote via hashtag. This creates a better buzz, engagement and people will pay attention when the spots come on. Not a bad attempt.

text: This video could've started with them entering the initial boardroom meeting. "Ok people focus up!" I like the idea of figuring out what HTC means because I never knew. (Don't think I cared but now I do). What's good is that it's a simple and fun idea. I think that instead of blowing the wad here they should break it up into several spots and turn to Twitter to have users submit their best ideas for what HTC means. Produce spots around the most entertaining ideas. Have people vote via hashtag. This creates a better buzz, engagement and people will pay attention when the spots come on. Not a bad attempt.

texts.html: Signing up Downey Jnr is a coup for HTC (beats the hell out of the Alicia Keys and Blackberry tie-up), and there's something interesting about the direction of this campaign, the execution of the idea leaves a bit to be desired. From a practitioner's point of view, HTC haven't displayed the courage of their convictions and the repeated shoe-horning of the HTC One into the ad feels forced.

text: Signing up Downey Jnr is a coup for HTC (beats the hell out of the Alicia Keys and Blackberry tie-up), and there's something interesting about the direction of this campaign, the execution of the idea leaves a bit to be desired. From a practitioner's point of view, HTC haven't displayed the courage of their convictions and the repeated shoe-horning of the HTC One into the ad feels forced.

texts.html: Then again, as an awareness raising effort it's probably a heck of a lot cheaper than the method that Samsung chose - being taken to court by Apple for ripping off the iPhone.
